      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055272_1822-06_page02.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <salute>
               Dear Sir
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p>
               Dear Sir,<lb/>
               Permit me to remind<lb/>
               you of half a promise<lb/>
               you made to lend<lb/>
               or give me an <choice>
                  <orig>Ameri-<lb/>
                  can</orig>
                  <reg>American</reg>
               </choice> poem which you<lb/>
               said I think was <choice>
                  <orig>some-<lb/>
                  what</orig>
                  <reg>somewhat</reg>
               </choice> in the style of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ByroG1">Lord<lb/>
               Byron</persName>. - I am anxious<lb/>
               to have this proof of<lb/>
               American genius in<lb/>
               my profession &amp; to <choice>
                  <orig>re-<lb/>
                  cieve</orig>
                  <reg>receive</reg>
               </choice> it as your gift<lb/>
               would much add to<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055272_1822-06_page03.jpg"/>
               its value in my eyes.<lb/>
               I have desired my<lb/>
               bookseller (<persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName> S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>.<lb/>
               Pauls Church Yard)<lb/>
               to send you the <title>memoirs<lb/>
                  of my father</title> which you<lb/>
               did me the honor<lb/>
               to say you would<lb/>
               accept - but <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName>
               <lb/>
               tells me that he has<lb/>
               not been able to find<lb/>
               you - <del>Will</del> If you<lb/>
               will have the goodness<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055272_1822-06_page04.jpg"/>
               to let some one call<lb/>
               at 72 S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. Pauls Ch Yard<lb/>
               the book will be<lb/>
               delivered to you -<lb/>
               I am glad of this<lb/>
               opportunity to<lb/>
               express the pleasure<lb/>
               I have had in <choice>
                  <orig>becom<lb/>
                  -ing</orig>
                  <reg>becoming</reg>
               </choice> acquainted with<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RandJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Randolph</persName>, and<lb/>
               in hearing the <choice>
                  <orig>judici<lb/>
                  ous</orig>
                  <reg>judicious</reg>
               </choice> manner in<lb/>
               which he speaks both<lb/>
               of <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7002445">England</placeName> and <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7012149">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Ameri<lb/>
                  -ca</orig>
                     <reg>America</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> - If ever <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RandJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Ran<lb/>
                  <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055272_1822-06_page05.jpg"/>
                  -dolph</persName> should visit<lb/>
               <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/7001181">Ireland</placeName>
               <del>Miss Edgew</del>
               <lb/>
               I hope he will not<lb/>
               forget to call at <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/tgn/1042937">
                  <choice>
                     <orig>Edge-<lb/>
                  worth's-Town</orig>
                     <reg>Edgeworth's-Town</reg>
                  </choice>
               </placeName> -<lb/>
            </p>
            <closer>
               <!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
               I am Dear Sir<lb/>
               with much esteem<lb/>
               Yours sincerely<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               June 13<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. 1822.<lb/>
            </closer>
            <pb n="5" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055272_1822-06_page06.jpg"/>
            <postscript>
               <p><!--A postscript goes here, outside the <closer>. -->
                  I seal with the rose,<lb/>
                  thistle &amp; shamrock -<lb/>
                  What is the American<lb/>
                  emblem? or is there<lb/>
                  one?<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
            <!-- Format for postscripts. 
               Postscripts do NOT go inside closer tags. Adjust to take into account the order in your letter. 
               Sometimes the signature is on page three, the address on page four, then the postscript follows back on the top of page one, for example.-->
            <pb n="6" facs="Edgeworth_UVA_000055272_1822-06_page01.jpg"/>
            <closer><!--Use the <closer> element again to hold Address Leaf information.-->
               <address>
                  <!--Include any text written on the address leaf; use a separate "addrLine" for each line and indicate line breaks. -->
                  <addrLine>
                     <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RandJ1">J. Randolph</persName> Esqr</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>3 Warwick Street</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>
                     <placeName>Spring Gardens</placeName>
                  </addrLine>
                  <note place="bottom">[LibNote]Miss Edgworth<lb/>
                     June 13, 1812[/LibNote]</note>
               </address>
